Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Negeri Sembilan is one of Malaysia's 13 states, situated on the western coast of Peninsular Malaysia, bordering Selangor on the north, Pahang in the east, and Malacca and Johor to the south (map at http://tinyurl.com/zh83teu).

There are some statements in the above media report which deserve clarification/correction:

1. _B. abortus_ infection in cattle is not regarded to be fatal. The disease is usually asymptomatic in young animals and non-pregnant females. Following infection, pregnant adult females develop a placentitis, usually resulting in abortion between the 5th and 9th month of pregnancy. The mammary gland and associated lymph nodes may also be infected, and organisms may be excreted in the milk. Subsequent pregnancies are usually carried to term, but uterine and mammary infection recurs, with reduced numbers of organisms in afterbirth products and milk. In acute infections, the organism is present in most major body lymph nodes. Adult male cattle may develop orchitis/epididymitis, and brucellosis may be a cause of infertility in both sexes.

2. Most human _B. abortus_ infections are direct, resulting from exposure to infected foeti, fetal fluids and vaginal discharges of attended cattle. Most indirect infections result from the consumption of unpasteurized milk and unpasteurized dairy products. While udders and testicles of infected cattle are of high risk, the consumption of meat (muscular tissue) from such animals is significantly less hazardous, and even allowed by some countries.

The Malaysian _B. abortus_ situation has recently been reviewed (Ref. 1). From the said reference, we hereby present the following extracted data.

The prevalence of bovine brucellosis _Brucella abortus_ in 2014 ranged between 1-2 percent in Thailand and Indonesia, and 4-5 percent in Malaysia and Myanmar. "Test-and slaughter" is the general policy against brucellosis adopted by most ASEAN [Association of Southeast Asian Nations] countries to eradicate the disease. Under this program, the Rose Bengal Plate Test (RBPT) is used as the screening test to identify infected farm/herd, while the complement fixation test (CFT) is the confirmatory test.

The "test-and-slaughter" method is expensive and internationally recommended as feasible only in countries where the prevalence rate does not exceed 2 percent and where surveillance and laboratory facilities are excellent. However, the small number of cattle in Malaysia of approximately 800 000 head made the program less expensive and feasible, and it was started in 1979.

The national bovine brucellosis eradication program had successfully reduced the prevalence of bovine brucellosis in Malaysia from 3.3 percent in 1979 to 0.23 in 1988 to approximately one percent in 1998, but was unable to eradicate the disease, which recurred to reach a prevalence of 5 percent in 2015. The failure of eradication was due to several factors, including inability to locate and identify the remaining affected animals and to control their movement, importation of breeder animals from non-brucellosis-free countries and lack of participation by the farmers who claimed that the program eliminated uninfected breeder animals following unreliable test results. To support the eradication policy, research activities since the 1980s have suggested combinations of serological tests to improve diagnosis, while surveillance should be focused on hot spot areas. The prevalence can be further reduced by strictly sourcing breeder animals from brucella-free areas or countries.

Reference
M. Zamri-Saad, M.I. Kamarudin. Control of animal brucellosis: The Malaysian experience. Asian Pacific Journal of Tropical Medicine 2016; 9(12): 1136-1140
http://tinyurl.com/hm6qurn (59 references). - Mod.AS

